products. In fact, most of the production here still works without electricity, so you get the impression that not much has changed here in the last 1,500 years. \nWe continue to Rishtan (approx. 1 hour drive), where we can visit a ceramics workshop. Rishtan is the most famous and oldest center of traditional ceramic production in Uzbekistan. You can also visit the pilgrimage site of Hazrat Hizr, which is very popular with locals but rarely visited by tourists. There are no impressive buildings to visit here (only a few saints' graves), but you get an impression of the traditional religiosity and folk beliefs of the Uzbeks. \nToday's destination in the Fergana Valley, after another 45 minutes' drive, is Kokand, from where we take the express train to the capital Tashkent. If we get here early enough, there will still be time to visit the intact, old center of the capital of the former Khanate of Kokand. According to the timetable, our train departs at 5:28 p.m. and reaches Tashkent at 9:20 p.m. \nLunch in one of the cities visited, dinner preferably in the train's dining car (both not included). \nTransfer to the hotel and overnight at the hotel in twin rooms. \nMeals: Breakfast at the hotel.\n	\N
